00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:49.040
What are Docker volumes?

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:54.340
So if you do Docker a lot, you know exactly what Docker volumes are.

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:59.080
But Docker's a little bit one of those things like, oh, it seems so complicated, so weird.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:01.540
And it's just really different than what I'm used to doing.

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:05.580
And then you work and go, that's kind of like Linux, but just in a file.

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:06.500
You know what I mean?

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:11.440
But one of the things that is different about Docker is it's very transient.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:21.540
It's not quite Nix that it can't be changed once it's fired up, but it's generally ephemeral, right?

00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:22.780
I start up a Docker container.

00:03:23.140 --> 00:03:27.640
My app or whatever app is running there might write to it, but that's right inside the Docker container.

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:36.480
And then when it goes away, if I restart it, rebuild it especially, then whatever it wrote is just gone.

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:37.740
Sometimes you want that.

00:03:38.420 --> 00:03:41.280
But say if you want your web server logs to stick around, you don't want it.

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:45.660
If you want your database data to stick around, you really don't want it.

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:55.960
So there's a lot of times that you want a permanent storage, but an ephemeral operated system and code and so on for Docker.

00:03:56.500 --> 00:04:08.300
So what you can create is a Docker volume, which is a managed, persistent, virtual hard drive type thing associated with that particular Docker container.

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:10.920
And you can move around theoretically afterwards, right?

00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:17.200
But typically you say, okay, my Docker setup, this database server gets a volume for its data, something like that.

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:17.820
Yeah.

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:21.360
And it's one of my favorite features of Docker is the immutability of the containers.

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:24.820
And if people respect that, things go a lot smoother generally.

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:25.720
Yes, exactly.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:30.820
Well, what I typically do, Calvin, when my Docker doesn't work, I just log into the container.

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:34.380
And then I like get pulled a new version and just like read.

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:35.000
No, just kidding.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.740
This is the modern equivalent of change mod 777 across all your files.

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:41.480
Exactly.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:42.180
It's not working.

00:04:42.260 --> 00:04:42.980
That always fixes it.

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:43.780
Just fix it.

00:04:44.020 --> 00:04:45.080
I just open all the ports.

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:46.140
It says it can't get to it.

00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:47.200
What's the problem?

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:47.680
These passwords.

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:48.400
Yeah, exactly.

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:52.040
So what do you do with those volumes, Michael?

00:04:53.060 --> 00:04:55.140
So you've got to back that data up.

00:04:55.560 --> 00:04:58.360
I mean, unless you just don't like yourself.

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:04.120
You've got to back up your data because if something goes wrong, from a whole host of reasons, things could go wrong.

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:05.800
You need a backup of your data.

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:07.780
That's just living in servers, right?

00:05:08.020 --> 00:05:08.940
Or just computers.

00:05:08.940 --> 00:05:13.380
So a lot of times what you can do is you can run some kind of command.

00:05:13.740 --> 00:05:15.120
Like I use MongoDB.

00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:16.820
A lot of these people, I also use Postgres.

00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:23.500
For either of those, there's a command you can run that says backup this and like back it up to the host or somewhere like that.

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:27.060
And then send it off to an encrypted storage or something.

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:36.100
But if it's just the hard drive, the volumes you want to back up specifically, that's way more challenging.

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:45.540
So Brian Weber, thanks Brian, sent over this idea called this Rust utility called Docker Volume Backup.

00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:55.600
And the idea is you can backup Docker Volumes to all the ways I can imagine I would possibly want to back them up.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:57.920
So you can back them up locally.

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:00.360
You can back them up to an S3 bucket.

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:05.580
And when you say S3, that means not just AWS that you can learn about tomorrow.

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:13.260
But many of the cloud storage, cloud providers have adopted some kind of S3 compatible API, right?

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:16.900
So you can back it up to, I don't know, Digitalization or something if you want as well.

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:21.900
WebDAV, Azure Blob Storage, which you probably could just treat as S3 of it directly.

00:06:22.360 --> 00:06:25.320
Dropbox, Google Drive, some SSH compatible storage.

00:06:25.400 --> 00:06:27.180
I'm guessing SCP or something like that.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:29.780
All those things.

00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:31.540
And how sweet is that?

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:41.520
So the idea is when you've got a Docker Compose type of setup, you can go and add a separate service, right?

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:46.800
And you're Compose and it just says the image is this project, this Docker Volume Backup.

00:06:47.460 --> 00:06:52.940
And you give it environment files and then it can just back up to somewhere.

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:55.740
Really, if it's easy to do, you will do it.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:06:57.360
Yes, it's nice, right?

00:06:57.580 --> 00:07:01.020
So you basically just add it as a separate service.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:01.480
Yeah.

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:05.300
And then in your ENV, you give it a schedule and a destination.

00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:07.560
You know, the ENV settings, right?

00:07:07.620 --> 00:07:08.380
The backup settings.

00:07:08.620 --> 00:07:09.760
You just give it those kinds of things.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:14.200
And if you've got a home lab and you've got a NAS on there, most NASs have S3 compatible storage.

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:15.160
So you can keep it all.

00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:21.040
I'm kind of touting the local first operation again, keeping all your data, your data.

00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:22.980
Yeah, absolutely.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:26.040
So this thing is super small, written in Go, 25 megs.

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:31.260
So there was also a Docker Volume Backup, Docker shell-based image.

00:07:31.260 --> 00:07:34.120
And this is 1 20th the size, so that's cool.

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:35.840
Let's see.

00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:41.460
You can set up a cron job in your Compose setup, or you can just CLI run it.

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:44.840
This is part of the stuff that I thought was really cool.

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:47.820
It rotates away your old backups, so you don't have to worry about that kind of stuff.

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:53.860
You say, like, just keep me a backup every day for a month, you know, or something like that.

00:07:53.860 --> 00:07:54.800
And then you move it on.

00:07:55.940 --> 00:08:01.960
Local GPT encryption, like at rest encryption of your backups, which I think is super important.

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:10.120
Because the last thing you want to do is, like, well, I want to make sure I back it up so it doesn't, if things get hacked, it doesn't go wrong, and then that actually being the thing that gets stolen.

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:15.400
Get notification on finished infield build, filled runs.

00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:23.520
You can have it stop the container before it does the snapshot and start it back up.

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:35.160
So if you're doing, like, I don't know, a SQLite sort of thing as your storage, and you don't need that much uptime, you want to make sure it's not in some, like, half-committed journaling state or whatever, you know.

