00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:36.640
But the next one up here actually is kind of exciting.

00:10:36.820 --> 00:10:44.120
Because it's not just a release of Pyodide 314, which you'll notice a new numbering scheme there going on.

00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:50.240
The real news here is actually the fact that PEP783 has made this possible.

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:59.260
The Pyodide maintainers were basically hand-building 300 plus packages for your browser to use Python in the browser.

00:10:59.380 --> 00:11:01.020
So this is all about using Python in the browser.

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:08.860
If you've ever thought about why do I have to use JavaScript to make fun web apps, you can actually use Python to do that with tools like Pyodide.

00:11:08.860 --> 00:11:27.100
And now that the 783 has actually been accepted, you can use cibuildwheel and put wheels like compiled binary packages onto PyPy so that if you write an app for the browser, someone can quickly download and get the latest versions of the dependencies you may be including in that application itself.

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:39.360
So again, they may be seeing a surge of browser-based Pyodide packages onto PyPy or PyPI coming up here in the future.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:42.900
But that's actually really cool to see that ease of use now.

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:47.360
So there's a whole tool chain available to build these packages and make them available.

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:51.340
A couple other changes that have happened in this 314 release.

00:11:51.460 --> 00:11:52.800
You'll notice the numbering change.

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:57.080
There's a version jump from 0.29 to 314.

00:11:57.300 --> 00:11:57.880
That's intentional.

00:11:58.180 --> 00:12:03.620
Basically, you're going to have the Pyodide version track the Python version that it closely matches with.

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:09.740
So if you're looking for the 3.12 version of Pyodide, that's the older 0.29.

00:12:10.220 --> 00:12:19.440
But moving forward, you'll quickly spot and know which version of Python you're getting when you install and use Pyodide in your projects based on the version number of Pyodide itself.

00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:23.820
So you'll get 314 tracks to 3.14.

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:32.400
So for binary compatibility, it's locked within the Python cycle, meaning the packages you build today won't break with the next Pyodide release.

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:35.060
So another big benefit to this piece here.

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:43.280
They've also brought back in some packages that were taken out of the standard library for Pyodide to make the packaging smaller.

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:50.960
Things like SQLite3, SSL, and LZMA are back in the default standard library, which is nice.

00:12:50.960 --> 00:12:56.720
So you don't have to basically install something like SQLite if you're using that in your browser-based application.

00:12:57.560 --> 00:13:00.300
There's some bug fixes and other things in there.

00:13:00.300 --> 00:13:07.560
There's also experimental TCP socket support in Node.js, and you can now connect Pyodide to a real database.

00:13:08.540 --> 00:13:17.740
So that's kind of a wordy, if you've got Python running in the browser, but you can't connect to a database or to sockets, you were kind of limited in what you could do with local storage, for example.

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:22.480
But now that opens up a wider spectrum of things you can do.

00:13:22.660 --> 00:13:27.580
It looks like they've tested it on MySQL, Postgres, and Redis when running on the server side.

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:36.180
So it definitely blurs the lines between Python in the browser and Python runtime anywhere Wasm runs, which I think is, again, super cool.

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:37.120
