So pairing well with something like that last tool you just mentioned is that a lot of agents and a lot of these agentic workflows are lacking the ability to recall memory in an efficient way.

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:08.740
So this next piece here is actually a tool you can add into your agentic workflow to do AI memory.

00:20:09.140 --> 00:20:11.440
So and more than just memory, memory that learns.

00:20:12.020 --> 00:20:14.400
So thinking about this memory problem is actually kind of hard.

00:20:14.740 --> 00:20:17.060
AIs forget everything between sessions, obviously.

00:20:17.060 --> 00:20:22.060
So you're constantly writing project specs, implementation detail plans.

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:24.300
You know, those are good, good practices.

00:20:24.300 --> 00:20:29.980
But wouldn't it be nice if it could remember like last Tuesday when you use this tool, this kind of output happened.

00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:33.260
And maybe in this context, it's actually better to use this other tool.

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:44.640
But that kind of that temporal, like using time and associating facts and details together isn't something that just a markdown memory.md file is going to help you out with.

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:48.780
So there's an open source tool called Hindsight from the folks at Vectorize.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:52.400
And they offer a cloud version of this, but you can run it locally.

00:20:52.900 --> 00:20:54.300
You can install it with Python.

00:20:54.480 --> 00:21:04.000
It's got, I think, adapters for all the major like Python, JavaScript, Node, etc. But basically what they're saying is, you know, simple vector search is not enough.

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:13.460
Even if you had a ChromaDB locally with your documents all loaded into it, that isn't enough to solve the problem about what did you do last spring, for example.

00:21:13.460 --> 00:21:18.400
Like the example they give here that requires temporal reasoning and not just semantic similarity.

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:33.880
So Hindsight attempts to add in this extra layer of temporal retrieval, which runs semantic keyword graph and temporal search in parallel to store, retrieve and reason over those memories.

00:21:34.100 --> 00:21:37.200
So you actually get kind of three main functions.

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:37.560
There's three.

00:21:37.660 --> 00:21:38.560
It's a simple API.

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:41.700
There's just retain, recall and reflect.

00:21:41.700 --> 00:21:47.860
And then it uses this temper technique to do the search across all in parallel.

00:21:47.860 --> 00:21:56.780
And then it brings it all together and it automatically consolidates the related facts into durable observations instead of piling up duplicates.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:22:07.300
So, again, preserving that context window, putting in what is most valuable when it means the most to what you're doing is probably the next step in memory.

00:22:07.300 --> 00:22:15.020
I think this is, again, a next front that has to be conquered is giving these agents better recall and memory.

00:22:15.480 --> 00:22:21.900
I think a lot of people got a little taste of this with OpenClaw, but OpenClaw's default memory, I don't think, gives you this level out of the box.

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:24.900
But you could integrate this into your existing OpenClaws.

00:22:25.460 --> 00:22:26.660
It is on GitHub.

00:22:26.860 --> 00:22:27.600
It's open source.

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:30.080
You can pip install HindsightAll.

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:34.260
And that actually brings down and installs the whole server end process.

00:22:34.480 --> 00:22:47.520
It includes like a blockchain, Llama Index, Pydantic AI, and Crew AI and more all kind of bundled together into a nice package that you can just start using with your Claude Code or cursor or whatever agent you want.

00:22:47.740 --> 00:22:52.700
You can now give it better memory that can actually learn from what you're doing along the way.

